n |accessdate=September 25, 2012}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"White Christmas\">\n{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.de/White-Christmas/dp/B00FO59EDA/ |title=White Christmas by Kelly Clarkson |language=German |publisher=Amazon.de |location=Germany |accessdate=October 7, 2013}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Greatest Hits \u2014 Chapter 1 release\">\n{{cite web|url=http://clizbeats.com/kelly-clarkson-set-to-release-greatest-hits-%E2%80%93-chapter-1-on-november-19thnew-single-%E2%80%9Ccatch-my-breath%E2%80%9D-set-to-impact-radio-and-available-for-sale-at-all-digital-providers-octobe1/ |title=Kelly Clarkson set to release 'Greatest Hits \u2014 Chapter 1' |work=RCA Records |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |accessdate=October 4, 2012}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Smoakstack 2 release\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.myplaydirect.com/kelly-clarkson/greatest-hits-chapter-one-smoakstack-sessions-vol-2/details/27815592 |title=Kelly Clarkson \u2014 Greatest Hits - Chapter One + Smoakstack Sessions - Vol. 2 |work=MyPlay Direct |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |accessdate=November 5, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108021848/http://www.myplaydirect.com/kelly-clarkson/greatest-hits-chapter-one-smoakstack-sessions-vol-2/details/27815592 |archivedate=November 8, 2012 }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Kelly Clarkson Live release\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/release/kelly-clarkson-live-mr0004653888 |title=Kelly Clarkson [Live] - Kelly Clarkson {{!}} Release Info |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=January 26, 2017}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Album - Wrapped in Red\">\n{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2013/08/19/kelly-clarkson-to-release-christmas-album/2671071/ |title=Kelly Clarkson to release first Christmas album |first=Elysa |last=Gardner |work=USA Today |publisher=Gannett Company |date=August 19, 2013 |accessdate=August 20, 2013}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Single - Silent Night\">\n{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/ca/album/silent-night-feat.-reba-mcentire/id751605874 |title=Silent Night (feat. Reba McEntire & Trisha Yearwood) - Single by Kelly Clarkson |location=Canada |work=iTunes Store |publisher=Apple Inc. |date=December 16, 2013 |accessdate=December 24, 2013}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Single - PrizeFighter\">\n{{cite web|url=http://www.sonymusicnashville.com/news/sony-nashville/77864/trisha-yearwoods-new-single-prizefighter-impacts-radio-september-15 |title=Trisha Yearwood's New Single \"PrizeFighter\" impacts radio on September 15 |work=[[Sony Music Nashville]] |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |date=August 25, 2014 |accessdate=August 26, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826140818/http://www.sonymusicnashville.com/news/sony-nashville/77864/trisha-yearwoods-new-single-prizefighter-impacts-radio-september-15 |archivedate=August 26, 2014 }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Digital Spy 1\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a631419/kelly-clarkson-unveils-john-legend-duet-run-run-run.html |title=Kelly Clarkson unveils John Legend duet 'Run Run Run' |first=Lewis |last=Corner |website=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]] |date=February 25, 2015 |accessdate=February 27, 2015 }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Piece by Piece Remixed\">\n{{cite web|last1=Wass|first1=Mike|title=Kelly Clarkson Releases Idol Version Of \"Piece By Piece,\" Announces Remix Album|url=http://www.idolator.com/7625173/kelly-clarkson-piece-by-piece-idol-version-remix-album|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|publisher=[[Spin Media]]|date=February 29, 2016|accessdate=February 29, 2016}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p542180|tab=discography|label=Kelly Clarkson discography}}\n* {{Discogs artist|Kelly Clarkson}}\n\n{{Kelly Clarkson}}\n{{Kelly Clarkson songs}}\n\n{{featured list}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clarkson, Kelly}}\n[[Category:American Idol discographies]]\n[[Category:Discographies of American artists]]\n[[Category:Kelly Clarkson|Discography]]\n[[Category:Pop music discographies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist          = [[Kelly Clarkson]]\n| Image           = File:Kelly Clarkson 2018 DoD Warrior Games Opening Ceremony 12.jpg\n| Caption         = Clarkson performing at the 2018 DoD [[Warrior Games]]\n| Studio          = 8\n| Compilation     = 1\n| EP              = 5\n| Singles         = 43\n| Option          = 1\n| Option name     = Remix albums\n| 1Option         = 14\n| 1Option name    = Promotional singles\n| 2Option         = 26\n| 2Option name    = Other appearances\n}}\nAmerican singer [[Kelly Clarkson]] has released eight [[Album|studio album]]s, five [[extended play]]s, one [[compilation album]], one [[remix album]], and 43 [[single (music)|singles]] (including four as a featured artist). In 2002, she won the [[American Idol (season 1)|inaugural season]] of the television competition ''[[American Idol]]'' and was immediately signed to a {{USD}}1 million recording deal with [[RCA Records]].<ref name=\"RCA Record Deal\" /> She made her chart debut in September 2002 with the [[A-side and B-side|double A-side]] single \"[[Before Your Love]]\" / \"[[A Moment Like This]]\", which topped the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart in the United States by achieving the [[List of Billboard Hot 100 chart achievements and milestones#Song achievements#Biggest jump to number one|biggest jump to number one]].<ref name=\"BillboarHot100Jump\" /> Her debut album, ''[[Thankful (Kelly Clarkson album)|Thankful]]'', was released in April 2003 and debuted atop the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart in the United States and was certified in four countries, including a [[RIAA certification|double-platinum]] certification by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA). Its lead single, \"[[Miss Independent (Kelly Clarkson song)|Miss Independent]]\", charted in nine countries, reaching number nine on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100. Subsequent singles from the album include \"[[Low (Kelly Clarkson song)|Low]]\" and \"[[The Trouble with Love Is]]\". In 2004, Clarkson released her second album, ''[[Breakaway (Kelly Clarkson album)|Breakaway]]'', which incorporated aspects of pop rock. ''Breakaway'' debuted at number three on the ''Billboard'' 200 and subsequently became her most successful studio album to date, being certified sextuple-platinum in the United States and twelve million worldwide.<ref name=\"Breakaway worldwide sales\" /> Its first four singles, \"[[Breakaway (Kelly Clarkson song)|Breakaway]]\", \"[[Since U Been Gone]]\", \"[[Behind These Hazel Eyes]]\", and \"[[Because of You (Kelly Clarkson song)|Because of You]]\", became successful hits worldwide, charting at the top-ten in many countries, and with the latter-most topping the charts in the Netherlands and Switzerland. Its final single, \"[[Walk Away (Kelly Clarkson song)|Walk Away]]\", became a top-twenty hit in many countries.\n\nClarkson's third studio album, ''[[My December]]'', which has a more rock-influenced sound than its predecessor, was released in June 2007. The album's release became a subject of a dispute with the music mogul and the then-Chairman and CEO of the [[RCA Music Group]] [[Clive Davis]], who wanted Clarkson to make significant changes and record new material for the album.<ref name=\"My December Time feature\" /><ref name=\"My December FOX News feature\" /> ''My December'' was later certified platinum by the RIAA, but failed to match the sales of its predecessor by suffering poor publicity for its uncommercial nature and thus became her least-commercially successful album in the United States to date. Its lead single, \"[[Never Again (Kelly Clarkson song)|Never Again]]\", became a top-ten hit in four countries, including the United States. Three more singles from the album, \"[[Sober (Kelly Clarkson song)|Sober]]\", \"[[One Minute]]\", and \"[[Don't Waste Your Time]]\", were released.\n\nIn March 2009, Clarkson released her fourth studio album, ''[[All I Ever Wanted (album)|All I Ever Wanted]]'', which contained elements of a more pop-oriented sound. The album debuted at the top of the ''Billboard'' 200 and became a commercial success. Its lead single \"[[My Life Would Suck Without You]]\", became an international hit; it topped the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 by breaking the record previously held by [[Britney Spears]]' \"[[Womanizer (song)|Womanizer]]\" for the biggest jump to number one in the chart's history<ref name=\"BillboarHot100Jump\" /> and topped the charts in the United Kingdom, Canada and Hungary. Four subsequent singles, \"[[I Do Not Hook Up]]\", \"[[Already Gone (Kelly Clarkson song)|Already Gone]]\", \"[[All I Ever Wanted (Kelly Clarkson song)|All I Ever Wanted]]\" and \"[[Cry (Kelly Clarkson song)|Cry]]\",<ref name=\"Single - Cry\" /> were released, with the foremost two becoming top-twenty hits worldwide. In October 2011, Clarkson released her fifth studio album, ''[[Stronger (Kelly Clarkson album)|Stronger]]''. Its first two singles, \"[[Mr. Know It All]]\" and \"[[Stronger (What Doesn't Kill You)]]\", became international top-ten hits, with the former topping the charts in Australia and South Korea and the latter topping the charts in the United States, Poland, and Slovakia. \"Stronger (What Doesn't Kill You)\" also became Clarkson's most commercially successful single in her career by selling over five million copies worldwide.<ref name=\"Stronger Worldwide single sales\" /> Its final single, \"[[Dark Side (Kelly Clarkson song)|Dark Side]]\", was released to moderate success. ''Stronger'' was eventually certified platinum by the RIAA.\n\nClarkson released her first [[greatest hits album]], ''[[Greatest Hits \u2013 Chapter One (Kelly Clarkson album)|Greatest Hits \u2013 Chapter One]]'',<ref name=\"Greatest Hits \u2014 Chapter 1 release\" /> in November 2012.<ref name=\"Single - Catch My Breath\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kellyclarkson.com/us/news/catch-my-breath |title=Kelly Clarkson \u2014 Catch My Breath \u2014 single release |work=KellyClarkson.com |publisher=[[Sony Music Entertainment]] |accessdate=October 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006232832/http://www.kellyclarkson.com/us/news/catch-my-breath |archivedate=October 6, 2012 }}</ref> Three songs were recorded for the compilation: \"[[Catch My Breath]]\", \"[[Don't Rush (song)|Don't Rush]]\" and \"[[People Like Us (Kelly Clarkson song)|People Like Us]]\"; all of which were released as singles.<ref name=\"Greatest Hits \u2014 Chapter 1 release\" /><ref name=\"Single - Catch My Breath\" /> ''Greatest Hits \u2013 Chapter One'' was eventually certified gold by the RIAA and was succeeded by the release of her sixth studio album and first [[Christmas album|Christmas-themed album]], ''[[Wrapped in Red]]'', in October 2013. The holiday album was accompanied by its singles \"[[Underneath the Tree]]\" and \"[[Wrapped in Red (song)|Wrapped in Red]]\".<ref name=\"Album - Wrapped in Red\" /> The album was quickly certified platinum by the RIAA. Clarkson released her seventh studio album, ''[[Piece by Piece (Kelly Clarkson album)|Piece by Piece]]'' in 2015, which spawned the singles \"[[Heartbeat Song (Kelly Clarkson song)|Heartbeat Song]]\", \"[[Invincible (Kelly Clarkson song)|Invincible]]\" and \"[[Piece by Piece (Kelly Clarkson song)|Piece by Piece]]\". She released her eighth studio album, ''[[Meaning of Life (album)|Meaning of Life]]'', on October 2017. The album included the singles \"[[Love So Soft]]\", \"[[I Don't Think About You]]\", and \"[[Heat (Kelly Clarkson song)|Heat]]\". According to the [[IFPI]] and [[Nielsen Soundscan]], Clarkson has sold over 25 million albums{{efn-ua|International members of the IFPI have certified Clarkson's tracks with 6,968,500 units sold, excluding the US-based RIAA (which has certified 12.5 million album units). In the United States, Nielsen Soundscan reported that Clarkson's albums have sold over 18.6 million units.<ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite web |title=Kelly Clarkson and John Legend to Perform at 2018 Billboard Music Awards |url=https://www.ctv.ca/The2018BillboardMusicAwards/Articles/News/Kelly-Clarkson-And-John-Legend-To-Perform |publisher=[[CTV Television Network|CTV]] |accessdate=October 3, 2019 |date=May 3, 2018}}</ref>}} and over 40 million songs.{{efn-ua|International members of the IFPI have certified Clarkson's tracks with 6,682,500 units sold, excluding the US-based RIAA (which has certified 14.5 million song units). In the United States, Nielsen Soundscan reported that Clarkson's tracks have sold over 35 million digital downloads.<ref name=\"CTV\" />}} In her native United States, she has sold over 50 million records\u2014which includes over 18.6 million [[equivalent album units]] (14 million traditional album copies),<ref name=\"bbsales\">{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7957889/ask-billboard-kelly-clarksons-career-sales-wild-thoughts-about |title=Ask Billboard: Kelly Clarkson's Career Sales & 'Wild Thoughts' About Rihanna |first=Gary |last=Trust |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |date=September 10, 2017 |accessdate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> 35 million digital tracks, and 1.5 billion on-demand streams.<ref name=\"CTV\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Kelly Clarkson, Khalid & More to Perform at the 2019 BBMAs |url=https://www.billboardmusicawards.com/2019/04/kelly-clarkson-khalid-more-to-perform-at-the-2019-bbmas/ |publisher=[[Dick Clark Productions]] |accessdate=October 3, 2019 |date=April 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Albums==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:11em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:19em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"10\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n! scope=\"co